#X text 25 27 We've seen Hard Sync in oscillators \, but the sound way cooler when their pitch (the slave frequency) is modulated. This is because the character of the sound changes a lot \, and this is something that is explored in sound synthesis in different ways as we'll see (next example is on pulse width modulation \, for instance)., f 61;
#X text 25 120 Below we have a decay envelope dropping the pitch from '43' semitones to '11' semitones in 3 seconds. This is in respect to the master frequency \, which stays unaltered. At 11 semitones \, it is a major seventh higher., f 61;
#X text 253 413 Instead of the decay envelope \, try patching this LFO into [+~] for another modulation example., f 31;
#X text 284 534 shifting from an octave plus a fifth (19 semitones) to a major seventh (11)., f 31;
#X text 810 208 And now we just increment the example by modulating the pitch input as well with a quick decay for both slave and master. Plus filtering \, overdrive and reverb., f 25;
#X text 788 412 Hint and excercize. You can try and expand this example to include a decay envelope to also control the filter cutoff. This is actually a Subtractive synthesis technique we'll see later. How about droping from 6.5k to 1.5k in 1.5 seconds?, f 35;
